.Dd April 11, 2026
.Dt MOXIN 7
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm moxin
.Nd declarative MCP tool configs for moxy
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
configs let you declare MCP tools as TOML files discovered via the
.Ev MOXIN_PATH
environment variable.
Each moxin is a directory containing a manifest and one or more tool
definitions.
.Xr moxy 1
handles all MCP protocol plumbing, process invocation, result caching,
and resource-as-fd composition natively \(em no Go code required.
.Pp
Moxins coexist with proxied MCP servers.
When a moxin has the same name as a moxyfile server,
the moxyfile server wins and the moxin is skipped.
.Sh CONFIG FORMAT
Each moxin is a directory containing a
.Pa _moxin.toml
manifest and one
.Pa .toml
file per tool:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
moxins/man/
  _moxin.toml           # server manifest
  toc.toml              # tool: list sections
  section.toml          # tool: read one section
  search.toml           # tool: semantic search
.Ed
.Ss Manifest (_moxin.toml)
The manifest declares the server identity:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
schema = 1
name = "man"
description = "Unix man page reader"
.Ed
.Ss Tool File (<tool-name>.toml)
Each tool file declares one tool.
The filename (without
.Pa .toml )
becomes the tool name:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
schema = 1
description = "List sections of a man page"
command = "sh"
args = ["-c", "...", "_"]

[input]
type = "object"
required = ["page"]

[input.properties.page]
type = "string"
description = "Man page name"
.Ed
.Ss Manifest Fields
.Bl -tag -width "description"
.It Sy schema
Schema version.
Currently must be
.Li 1 .
.It Sy name
Server name.
Must not contain dots (the dot is the tool namespace separator).
.It Sy description
Optional human-readable description of the server.
.El
.Ss Tool Fields
.Bl -tag -width "perms-request"
.It Sy schema
Schema version.
Currently must be
.Li 1 .
.It Sy description
Human-readable description shown to agents.
.It Sy command
Executable to run.
Resolved from
.Ev PATH
or as a relative path from the working directory.
.It Sy args
Optional array of arguments prepended before caller-supplied arguments.
.It Sy input
Optional JSON Schema object describing the tool's parameters.
If present, must include
.Sy type = \(dqobject\(dq
(injected defensively if missing).
.It Sy perms-request
Permission request mode for this tool.
See
.Sx PERMISSIONS .
.El
.Sh PERMISSIONS
Each tool may declare a
.Sy perms-request
field that controls how moxy communicates with the client's permission
hook:
.Bl -tag -width "delegate-to-client"
.It Li always-allow
The permission hook returns
.Dq allow ,
skipping the user confirmation prompt.
Use for read-only or idempotent tools.
.It Li each-use
The permission hook returns
.Dq ask ,
forcing the client to prompt the user for confirmation on every
invocation.
Use for destructive or sensitive operations.
.It Li delegate-to-client
No hook output is produced; the client applies its own policy.
This is the default when
.Sy perms-request
is omitted.
.El
.Sh DISCOVERY
Moxin configs are discovered from directories listed in the
.Ev MOXIN_PATH
environment variable (colon-separated, like
.Ev MANPATH ) .
Earlier entries override later ones by server name.
Within each path entry, subdirectories containing a
.Pa _moxin.toml
file are recognized as moxins.
.Pp
The executable-relative
.Pa <prefix>/share/moxy/moxins/
directory (system moxins) is automatically appended as the lowest-priority
entry, unless
.Sy builtin-native = false
is set in the moxyfile.
.Pp
The
.Sy moxy moxin-path
subcommand generates a default
.Ev MOXIN_PATH
from the legacy hierarchy convention:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
<cwd>/.moxy/moxins:<intermediate>/.moxy/moxins:~/.config/moxy/moxins:<systemDir>
.Ed
.Pp
Only existing directories are included.
.Sh ARGUMENT PASSING
Caller-supplied arguments are extracted from the MCP
.Sy tools/call
request, converted to strings, and appended after
.Sy args
in a deterministic order:
.Pp
.Bl -enum -compact
.It
Keys listed in the input schema's
.Sy required
array, in order.
.It
Remaining keys, sorted lexicographically.
.El
.Pp
For
.Sy sh -c
tools, this means the caller's arguments become positional
parameters
.Sy $1 , $2 , ...
when
.Sy args
ends with
.Dq _ .
.Sh RESULT CACHING
Tool outputs exceeding 50 tokens are cached to disk at
.Pa $XDG_CACHE_HOME/moxy/native-results/
(or
.Pa ~/.cache/moxy/native-results/ )
and replaced with a summary:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
Full output: moxy.native://results/{session}/{id}
Lines: 393

--- First 10 lines ---
\&...

--- Last 10 lines ---
\&...
.Ed
.Pp
Caching is transparent and server-level \(em no per-tool configuration.
When output exceeds the threshold, the summary includes prominent
truncation warnings so agents know data was omitted.
.Pp
.Sy "Moxins must not implement their own truncation" .
Do not add
.Sy head , tail ,
or
.Sy max_bytes
parameters that silently cut output \(em agents cannot distinguish
truncated output from complete output, leading to false conclusions.
The framework handles all truncation centrally with clear signaling.
.Pp
Moxins
.Em may
implement
.Sy scope-limiting
parameters that constrain what the tool
.Em produces ,
as opposed to truncating what it already produced.
For example,
.Sy max_patch_lines
in a diff tool limits how much git generates,
and
.Sy top_k
in a search tool limits result cardinality.
The distinction: scope limits change the query;
truncation discards part of the answer.
.Pp
.Sy "Wrong" \(em
truncation parameter that silently discards output:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
# DON'T: agent has no way to know output was cut
if [ -n "$tail_n" ]; then
  echo "$output" | tail -n "$tail_n"
elif [ -n "$head_n" ]; then
  echo "$output" | head -n "$head_n"
else
  echo "$output"
fi
.Ed
.Pp
.Sy "Right" \(em
scope parameter that limits what the tool asks for:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
# OK: limits the query, not the answer
rg_args+=(--max-count "$max_matches")
.Ed
The session identifier is resolved at
.Xr moxy 1
startup using a fallback chain:
.Ev CLAUDE_SESSION_ID ,
then
.Ev SPINCLASS_SESSION_ID ,
then a generated UUID.
.Sh RESOURCE-AS-FD COMPOSITION
When a tool argument contains a
.Sy moxy.native://results/{session}/{id}
URI, the native server:
.Pp
.Bl -enum -compact
.It
Loads the cached output from disk.
.It
Creates an OS pipe and streams the content through it.
.It
Rewrites the URI to
.Pa /dev/fd/N
in the argument string.
.El
.Pp
This allows tool outputs to be composed as inputs to subsequent tools
without the agent needing to manage temporary files.
For example, a cached transcript can be piped through
.Xr tail 1 :
.Bd -literal -offset indent
tail -5 moxy.native://results/no-session/019d7262-e6b3
.Ed
.Pp
becomes:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
tail -5 /dev/fd/3
.Ed
.Sh COMMAND PATTERNS
.Ss Shell One-Liners
For simple pipelines using only coreutils-level commands, use
.Sy sh -c
with positional arguments:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
command = "sh"
args = ["-c", "cat \(dq$1\(dq | wc -l", "_"]
.Ed
.Pp
The
.Dq _
sets
.Sy $0 ;
caller arguments become
.Sy $1 , $2 , ... .
.Pp
Note that TOML multiline basic strings
.Pf ( Dq \(dq\(dq\(dq...\(dq\(dq\(dq )
interpret backslash escapes.
Use
.Sy \e\en
to produce a literal
.Sy \en
in the shell script.
.Pp
Tools that depend on non-coreutils binaries should ensure those
binaries are available at runtime
.Pq e.g. via wrapper scripts, Nix shebangs, or package manager integration .
Inline
.Sy sh -c
commands that call external tools will fail if those tools are not on
.Ev PATH .
.Ss External Scripts
For complex logic, point
.Sy command
at a standalone script:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
command = ".moxy/bin/my-tool"
.Ed
.Pp
Scripts can use
.Xr nix 1
shebangs to declare their own dependencies:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
#!/usr/bin/env nix
#! nix shell nixpkgs#python3 --command python3

import json, os, sys
from pathlib import Path
\&...
.Ed
.Pp
This keeps scripts self-contained and reproducible without requiring
dependencies to be on the ambient
.Ev PATH .
.Ss Choosing Between Patterns
Shell one-liners work well for simple pipelines
(rendering, formatting, wrapping a single binary).
External scripts are better when:
.Pp
.Bl -dash -compact
.It
The logic involves loops over many files (avoid per-file subprocess forks).
.It
JSON parsing is needed (Python's
.Sy json
module vs.
.Xr jq 1
in a loop).
.It
The script exceeds ~10 lines.
.El
.Sh NIX PACKAGING
Builtin moxins shipped with
.Xr moxy 1
use a three-part pattern to ensure helper scripts are hermetic and
reproducible under Nix.
.Ss Libexec Directory
Helper scripts that tools invoke live in
.Pa $out/libexec/moxy/ ,
following the FHS convention for
.Dq programs called by other programs, not by users .
This is the same pattern used by
.Xr git 1
.Pq Pa libexec/git-core/ ,
.Nm x11-ssh-askpass ,
and other nixpkgs packages.
.Pp
Scripts are grouped by moxin name prefix
.Pq e.g. Li freud-sessions , Li just-list-recipes
so they can be wrapped in bulk.
.Ss Placeholder Substitution
Tool TOML files reference scripts via a build-time placeholder:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
command = "@LIBEXEC@/freud-sessions"
.Ed
.Pp
During the Nix build, the placeholder is replaced with the absolute
store path
.Pq e.g. Pa /nix/store/\&...-moxy-0.1.0/libexec/moxy
using
.Fn replaceVars
or equivalent.
This decouples the TOML source from the final install location.
.Pp
The
.Fn replaceVars
function (successor to the deprecated
.Fn substituteAll )
is preferred over ad-hoc
.Xr sed 1
because it fails the build if any placeholder goes unsubstituted,
catching typos at build time.
.Ss Dependency Wrapping
Each helper script is wrapped with
.Xr wrapProgram 1
to inject its runtime dependencies:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
for f in $out/libexec/moxy/freud-*; do
  wrapProgram "$f" \e
    --set PATH ${pkgs.python3}/bin
done
.Ed
.Pp
Using
.Fl -set
instead of
.Fl -prefix
makes scripts fully hermetic \(em they see only Nix-provided binaries
and cannot accidentally depend on the ambient
.Ev PATH .
.Pp
Dependencies are grouped by moxin name prefix, so all scripts for a
given moxin share the same wrapped
.Ev PATH .
.Ss Design Rules
.Bl -dash -compact
.It
Never rely on tools being on the ambient
.Ev PATH .
Outside the moxy devshell, they will not be available.
.It
Inline
.Sy sh -c
commands are acceptable only for coreutils-level builtins
.Pq Sy cat , echo , sed , wc .
Everything else goes to a libexec script.
.It
Put scripts in
.Pa libexec/ ,
wrap them in
.Pa flake.nix
with
.Fn wrapProgram ,
and reference them via the
.Li @LIBEXEC@
placeholder in the TOML config.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
.Ss Go Documentation Moxin
Directory layout:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
moxins/hamster/
  _moxin.toml
  doc.toml
  src.toml
.Ed
.Pp
.Pa _moxin.toml :
.Bd -literal -offset indent
schema = 1
name = "hamster"
description = "Go package documentation"
.Ed
.Pp
.Pa doc.toml :
.Bd -literal -offset indent
schema = 1
description = "Show documentation for a Go package or symbol."
command = "sh"
args = ["-c", """
set -euo pipefail
pkg="$1"
if [ -n "${2:-}" ]; then
  go doc "$pkg.$2"
else
  go doc "$pkg"
fi
""", "_"]

[input]
type = "object"
required = ["package"]

[input.properties.package]
type = "string"
description = "Go package path"

[input.properties.symbol]
type = "string"
description = "Exported symbol name"
.Ed
.Ss Session Transcript Moxin (Python Script)
Directory layout:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
moxins/freud/
  _moxin.toml
  sessions.toml
.Ed
.Pp
.Pa _moxin.toml :
.Bd -literal -offset indent
schema = 1
name = "freud"
description = "Past Claude Code session transcripts"
.Ed
.Pp
.Pa sessions.toml :
.Bd -literal -offset indent
schema = 1
description = "List past Claude Code sessions."
command = "/path/to/freud-sessions"

[input]
type = "object"
.Ed
.Pp
Where
.Pa freud-sessions
is a Python script that walks
.Pa ~/.claude/projects/
using
.Fn os.scandir
and
.Fn os.stat
instead of per-file subprocess forks.
Ensure
.Xr python3 1
is available via the script's shebang, a wrapper, or the ambient
.Ev PATH .
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr moxy 1 ,
.Xr moxyfile 5
.Sh STATUS
.Sy Experimental .
The config format, caching semantics, and fd substitution protocol
are subject to change.
Resource template declarations are not yet supported;
all native capabilities are exposed as tools.
